[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-alaska] In 2014, a poll by the Pew Research Center reported that 63% of adults in the state of Alaska believe abortion should be legal in all or most cases, with 34% stating it should be illegal in all or most cases.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-alaska] Alaska, Hawaii, Washington, and New York were the only four states that made abortion legal between 1967 and 1970 that did not require a reason to request an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-alaska] In 1970, the state repealed some of its abortion laws, along with Hawaii, New York, and Washington.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-alaska] The following year, Alaska repealed its statute that said inducing an abortion was a criminal offense.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-alaska] State law still required in 1971 that any woman getting a legal abortion in the state needed to be a resident for some specific period between 30 and 90 days.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-alaska] Some states, such as Alaska, Mississippi, West Virginia, Texas, and Kansas, have passed laws requiring abortion providers to warn patients of a link between abortion and breast cancer, and to issue other scientifically unsupported warnings.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-alaska] The state was one of 23 states in 2007 to have a detailed abortion-specific informed consent requirement.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-alaska] Alaska and Minnesota both require that women seeking abortions after 20 weeks be informed that, while experts disagree on the issue of whether or not a fetus can feel pain at 20 weeks, it is possible.
