[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-alaska] In May 2019, Eastman introduced House Bill 178, which defines abortion as "murder of an unborn child"; the bill was never heard before a committee.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-alaska] In 2022, Governor Mike Dunleavy expressed interest in an amendment to the Alaska Constitution clarifying the legality of abortion in the state.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-alaska] 2022 happened to be the year that Alaska's regularly scheduled ballot question for calling a state constitutional convention was asked.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-alaska] Dunleavy and other anti-abortion advocates recommended voting "yes", but the question was resoundingly defeated, with 70% voting "no".
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-alaska] In 2023, the bipartisan coalition majority in the Alaska State Senate is consensus-focused and unlikely to address controversial topics like abortion.
