[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] In a 2014 poll by Pew Research Center, 49% of Arizona adults said that abortion should be legal in all or most cases, with 47% saying it should be illegal in all or most cases.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] In a 2022 poll of 938 registered Arizona voters by OH Predictive Insights, 87% said they wanted abortion to remain legal in all or some cases.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Arizona's first ban on abortion was passed as part of the 1864 Howell Code, a year after the formation of the Arizona Territory (Arizona would not become a state until 1912).
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Physicians, however, were arrested for performing abortions.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] In the 19th century, bans by state legislatures on abortion were about protecting the life of the mother, given the number of deaths caused by abortions; state governments saw themselves as looking out for the lives of their citizens.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] By 1950, the state legislature would pass a law stating that a woman who had an abortion, or actively sought to have an abortion, regardless of whether she went through with it, were guilty of a criminal offense.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] By 1950, abortion was a criminal offense in Arizona.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals overturning Arizona's April 2012 abortion law in January 2015, the law banning abortion remains on the books.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] § 13-3603 was declared unconstitutional in 1973, in *Nelson v.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] The case was initially heard in 1972, when it declared the law constitutional.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Only the decision in *Roe* changed the court's decision, in a brief rehearing in 1973.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] But the Arizona legislature never struck the law from the books.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] As part of the statutes around abortion clinic regulations in Arizona and Florida that existed in 2007, there is a requirement that abortion providers show women ultrasounds of their fetus before they are allowed to have an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Governor Jan Brewer signed into law in April 2012 abortion restrictions that prohibited the procedure after 20 weeks.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] In April 2012, abortion after 20 weeks of pregnancy became illegal in Arizona; however, enforcement of the ban was permanently blocked under an injunction.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Targeted Regulation of Abortion Providers (TRAP) existed by 2013.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] In 2013, state TRAP law applied to medication-induced abortions and private doctor offices.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] In 2018, the state legislature passed a law that required the Arizona Health Department to apply for Title X funds as part of their attempts to defund Planned Parenthood.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Arizona law requires that only medical doctors can perform abortions, as of 2019.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Women have a mandated 24-hour waiting period after seeking an abortion, and must undergo in-person state-mandated counseling.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] On January 1, 2019, a new law came into force in Arizona that required women to provide detailed medical information that was to be submitted to the state before they were allowed to have an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Among the information the new law required abortion providers to collect was whether the abortion was elective or therapeutic, the number of abortions they have had in the past and information on any medical complications they have as a result of the abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] This information is then collected by Department of Health Services, which provides the state with an annual report on abortions in the state, along with information on how the abortions are paid for in the state.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] In 2019, women in Arizona were eligible for pregnancy-related disability-associated medical care that included abortion or miscarriage.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] As of May 14, 2019, abortion was legally not allowed after the fetus was viable, generally some point between week 24 and 28.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] This period uses a standard defined by the US Supreme Court in 1973 with the *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] The proposed legislation also said funds for this program "may not be used for abortion referral services or distributed to entities that promote, refer for, or perform abortions".
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Jackson Women's Health Organization* decision overturned *Roe*.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] The passing of Senate Bill 1164 in March 2022, combined with the overturning of *Roe*, restricted abortions to before 15 weeks of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] 1164 went into effect 90 days after the legislative session ended on June 30.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] 1164 was found not to control abortion in its entirety given that § 13-3603, which bans abortion entirely, is still on the books.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] These "dueling" laws led to a legal challenge.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] The injunction, which was lifted on September 23, 2022, by Pima County Superior Court Judge Kellie L.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Johnson, was temporarily reinstated by the Arizona Court of Appeals on October 7, 2022.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] On December 30, 2022, the Arizona Court of Appeals ruled that the criminal penalties of the 1864 law could not be enforced.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] On April 9, 2024, the Arizona Supreme Court ruled in *Planned Parenthood Arizona v.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Mayes* that the 1864 law could be enforced, to take effect 14 days later, but with no retroactive enforcement.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] As a result, abortion in Arizona temporarily became *de jure* illegal, except for when it is "necessary to save" the life of the pregnant woman.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] There were no exceptions for rape or incest, and the legally prescribed sentence for assisting in an illegal abortion is 2-5 years in prison.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] On April 26, 2024, the Arizona Supreme Court tersely rejected the Arizona Attorney General's motion for them to reconsider their decision.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Arizona Attorney General Kris Mayes, a Democrat, responded to the Arizona Supreme Court decision by declaring that "as long as I am Attorney General, no woman or doctor will be prosecuted under this draconian law in this state".
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Mayes criticized the Arizona Supreme Court for having "risked the health and lives of Arizonans", after "effectively striking down a law passed this century and replacing it with one from 160 years ago ... when Arizona wasn't a state, the Civil War was raging, and women couldn't even vote".
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Mayes later noted that another legal case in the Arizona Superior Court had delayed allowing enforcement of the 1864 law to be able to begin on June 8, 2024.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] In the Arizona House of representatives, Republican Representatives blocked attempts to repeal the 1864 law on April 10 and April 17, but later, on April 24, three Republican representatives sided with all the Democratic representatives in passing a repeal of the 1864 law, 32–28.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] In the Arizona Senate, Republican senators blocked a repeal attempt on April 10, but later, on May 1, two Republican senators joined all Democratic senators in passing a repeal of the 1864 law by a 16–14 vote.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] On May 2, 2024, Arizona Governor Katie Hobbs signed the bill to repeal the 1864 ban.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] In May 2024, the Arizona Supreme Court accepted Attorney General Mayes' request to further stay the 1864 abortion law, as they stayed enforcement of the 1864 abortion law until August 12, 2024.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Mayes responded that the stay applied in the other legal case would result in another delay of enforcement to September 26, 2024.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] The repeal took effect 90 days after the legislative session ends, on September 14, 2024.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Arizona for Abortion Access, a campaign intending to introduce a November 2024 ballot proposal to protect abortion rights within the Arizona Constitution, gathered signatures up to July 2024 for their petition to introduce the amendment.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] On July 3, 2024, it was reported that the organizers working on getting signatures to get the initiative on the ballot submitted 823,685 signatures for the measure.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] The required amount to qualify is 383,923 signatures.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Given the organizers exceeded the requirement by quite a bit, it is more likely to have qualified, barring future issues.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] On November 5, 2024, 2024 Arizona Proposition 139 was approved by voters.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] It established a right to abortion in the Constitution of Arizona up until fetal viability, which was re-affirmed by an Arizona court in March 2025.
