[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Planned Parenthood received around 17% of these funds while serving around 53% of all Title IX recipients.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Margaret Mary McBride is a Sister of Mercy.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] McBride was an administrator and member of the ethics committee at St.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Joseph's Hospital and Medical Center, which is owned by Catholic Healthcare West (Dignity Health).
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] On November 27, 2009, the committee was consulted on the case of a 27-year-old woman who was eleven weeks pregnant with her fifth child and suffering from pulmonary hypertension.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Her doctors stated that the woman's chance of dying if the pregnancy was allowed to continue was "close to 100 percent".
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] McBride joined the ethics committee in approving the decision to terminate the pregnancy through an induced abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] The abortion took place and the mother survived.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Afterwards, the abortion came to the attention of Bishop Thomas J.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Olmsted, the bishop of the Catholic Diocese of Phoenix.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Olmsted spoke to McBride privately and she confirmed her participation in the procurement of the abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Olmsted informed her that in allowing the abortion, she had incurred a *latae sententiae*, or automatic, excommunication.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] McBride was subsequently reassigned from her post as vice president of mission integration at the hospital.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] In December 2010, Olmsted announced that the Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix was severing its affiliation with the hospital, after months of discussion had failed to obtain from the hospital management a promise not to perform abortions in the future.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] "If we are presented with a situation in which a pregnancy threatens a woman's life, our first priority is to save both patients.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] If that is not possible, we will always save the life we can save, and that is what we did in this case," said hospital president Linda Hunt.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] On May 21, 2019, large number of women protested abortion laws passed in other states outside the Arizona Capitol building.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Protests began in Phoenix around 7:00 p.m.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] MST June 24, 2022 in response to the overturning of *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Demonstrations moved to the Arizona State Capitol, with it being mostly peaceful.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Protestors began banging on the building around 8:30 pm, prompting an evacuation of lawmakers and staff, which led to SWAT officers being deployed around the building.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] The protests were later called "an insurrection aimed at overthrowing the state government" by Republican Senate President Karen Fann; the Arizona Department of Public Safety fired tear gas when protestors attempted to break into the building.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] On June 25 a smaller number of people protested, with four people arrested on suspicion of rioting and disorderly conduct, including an identified member of the National Lawyers Guild Legal observer.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Protestors marched through Phoenix again on July 1.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] On January 20, 2024, thousands of abortion rights protesters rallied and marched at more than 100 Women's March events nationwide, with the main events held in Phoenix, Arizona and Washington, DC.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] On April 9, 2024, an abortion-rights protest was held in Phoenix following the Arizona Supreme Court's decision to allow a near-total abortion ban from 1864 to take effect.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] On April 11, 2024, Democrats in the Arizona state senate began chanting "Shame!
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Shame on you!" following the Republicans' decision to block an effort by Democrats to repeal the 1864 ban.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] On April 17, 2024, hundreds of abortion rights protesters rallied outside of the Arizona State Capitol in Phoenix.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] On June 8, 2024, Vote For Abortion kicked off its campaign with a bus tour across Phoenix, ending with a rally outside the Arizona State House.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] One notable 1962 case dealt with a woman named Sherri Finkbine.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] An Arizona resident since 1958, Finkbine then had four healthy children, ages 7, 5, 3, and 18 months.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] During her pregnancy with her fifth child, she discovered the child might have severe deformities.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Finkbine had been taking sleeping pills that contained a drug called thalidomide, which was also very popular in several countries.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] She had later learned that the drug was causing fetal deformities and she wanted to warn the general public.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Finkbine strongly wanted an abortion; however, the abortion laws of Arizona limited her decision.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] In Arizona, an abortion could only occur if the mother's life was in danger.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Physicians at Good Samaritan Hospital approved a therapeutic abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] However, prior to the scheduled procedure, Finkbine told her story to *The Arizona Republic* to warn other women about the dangers of the drug.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] At her request, the newspaper did not publish her name; however, it did publish enough information to identify her.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] The hospital, seeking to avoid exposure to criminal proceedings against its physicians, sought a declaratory judgment that the scheduled therapeutic abortion met the exception to the Arizona law banning all abortions except where necessary to save the life of the mother.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] The court denied the request on procedural grounds.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] On August 5, 1962, Finkbine traveled to Sweden, where after a two-week evaluation, she was able to obtain a legal abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-arizona] Swedish physicians confirmed the fetus was severely malformed.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Outpatient abortion is available up to 26 weeks.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In addition, medically indicated termination of pregnancy up to term is also an option for conditions such as fetal anomalies, genetic disorder, fetal demise and/or severe medical problems.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] 2024 Colorado Amendment 79 appeared on the ballot in November 2024.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] The amendment was approved, explicitly conferring a right to abortion in the Colorado state constitution.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 1962, the American Law Institute published their model penal code as it applied to abortions with three circumstances where they believed a physician could justifiably perform an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] A version of this was enacted into law in 1967.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Colorado became the first state to decriminalize abortion in cases of rape, incest, or in which pregnancy would lead to permanent physical disability of the woman.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] The first documented time "abortion" was mentioned in Colorado newspapers was in the Rocky Mountain News on September 30, 1867.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Back then, midwives used herbs to try to end pregnancies, but this could be very dangerous.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] The first documented arrest for abortion is J.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Mary Solander from Boulder was the first person sentenced to prison for abortion in 1873.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 1891, Colorado adopted Senate Bill 310, which further criminalized procuring an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In the early 1900s, newspapers reported more cases of doctors being charged.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 1909, osteopaths were prohibited from performing abortions.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 1929, the Colorado Assembly tried to make it legal for doctors to talk to married couples about birth control.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] But this law was killed in the Colorado Senate after heated debate.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] The proposed law was a partial repeal of the 1873 Comstock Act that made it illegal to distribute birth control materials.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Specifically, the new law permitted an abortion in cases of rape, incest, fetal abnormality, and to protect the life of the mother.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] However, it was only up to 16 weeks of pregnancy and required the husband's permission and approval from three doctors.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Over 33 months, 1,500 Colorado women obtained legal abortions, while around 20,000 sought illegal abortions because of the costs and red tape.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 1969, lawmakers failed to pass a bill that would have removed liability for a doctor or hospital refusing to perform an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 1973, the US Supreme Court's decision in *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] During the winter of 1978, three women in less than a month required hospitalization in Denver after consuming pennyroyal oil for the purpose of trying to induce an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 1978, Colorado set up Medicaid funding to help poor women get abortions.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 1979, a bill to ban public funding of abortions failed.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 1984, voters approved a similar constitutional amendment.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Between 1982 and 1992, the number of abortion clinics in the state decreased by fourteen, going from 73 in 1982 to 59 in 1992.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 1993, Colorado enacted speech restrictions within 100 feet of abortion clinics, a policy the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Colorado Republicans introduced numerous bills to ban or restrict abortion in almost all cases, beginning in 1997 and continuing through 2025.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] These bills did not pass due to Democratic opposition.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 2025, proposed bills backed by Republicans to ban abortion and prosecute women that had abortions were defeated.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 1998, Becky Bell's parents worked against proposed parental notification laws in Colorado.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 2006, pharmacists in Colorado were allowed to provide emergency contraception.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 2008, Colorado's Department of Public Health and Environment was provided with private funds to provide poor women in the state with long-acting reversible contraceptives (LARCs) at little or no cost to them.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] From 2009 to 2017, free, low-cost IUDs resulted in a 54% decline in the rate of teenage pregnancy in the state.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 2014, there were 21 abortion clinics in the state, and 78% of the counties in the state did not have an abortion clinic.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] That year, 27% of women in the state aged 15 – 44 lived in a county without an abortion clinic.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 2008, Kristine Burton and Michael Burton of Colorado for Equal Rights jointly proposed the Colorado Amendment 48 initiative.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Colorado Right to Life supported the amendment.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] The text would have amended the definition of a person to "any human being from the moment of fertilization".
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] This definition would have applied to all sections of Colorado law, thus giving a fetus the equal rights of life, liberty, and property as a fully developed, born person would.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] On November 4, 2008, the initiative was turned down by 73.2 percent of the voters.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Colorado Proposition 115 was a 2020 ballot initiative preventing abortion after 22 weeks unless the pregnancy endangered the mother's life.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Performing an abortion after 22 weeks would have become a Class 1 misdemeanor.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] On November 3, 2020, Colorado voters rejected Proposition 115, with 59% of voters opposed to the initiative.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In March 2016, there were 21 Planned Parenthood clinics in the state.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] After Planned Parenthood of the Rocky Mountains switched from directly billing women to directly billing Medicaid in 2016, it ran into funding bills as Medicaid has low reimbursement rates.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Consequently, it was forced to close two clinics in Colorado and one in Wyoming in July 2017.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 2017, there were nineteen Planned Parenthood clinics, of which eleven offered abortion services, in a state with a population of 1,278,937 women aged 15–49.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 2019, women in Colorado were eligible for temporary disability as a result of abortion or miscarriage.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] On April 4, 2022, Governor Jared Polis signed the Reproductive Health Equity Act, which guarantees access to reproductive care and affirms the rights of pregnant women to continue or terminate a pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] The act prohibits public entities from restricting or denying those rights.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, No.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] On April 18, 2024, Coloradans For Protecting Reproductive Freedom submitted nearly double the signatures required to put abortion rights on the ballot in Colorado in the November 2024 elections.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] 2024 Colorado Amendment 79 enshrined the right to abortion in the Colorado state constitution.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] 59% of adults said in a 2014 Pew Research Center poll that abortion should be legal in all or most cases and 36% said it should be illegal in all or most cases.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] The 2023 American Values Atlas reported that, in their most recent survey, 65% of Coloradans said that abortion should be legal in all or most cases.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 1990, 426,000 women in the state faced the risk of an unintended pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Since the start of the 2008 Colorado Family Planning Initiative, the number of abortions performed in the state fell by nearly half for women between the ages of 15–19.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] For women aged 20–24, the rate of abortions declined by 18%.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] For teens aged 15–19, the birth and abortion rate in Colorado between 2009 and 2014 declined around 50%.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] For women aged 20–24, the abortion rate declined by 20%.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 2010, the state had no publicly funded abortions.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 2013, there were 700 abortions for white women aged 15–19, 110 abortions for black women aged 15–19, 470 abortions for Hispanic women aged 15–19, and 90 abortions for women of all other races.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 2014, 59% of adults said in a poll by the Pew Research Center that abortion should be legal and 36% saying it should be illegal in all or most cases.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In 2017, the state had an infant mortality rate of 4.5 deaths per 1,000 live births.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] From 2009 to 2017, the rate of teenage abortions in the state fell by 64%.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In state politics, the Colorado Democratic Party largely support access to abortion and have passed legislation to protect and increase the accessibility of the procedure.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Wade overturn draft leak on May 2, 2022, there were abortion rights demonstrations in Aspen, Colorado Springs, Denver, Fort Collins, and Grand Junction.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Wade on June 24, 2022, an abortion rights protest was held outside the Colorado State Capitol in Denver.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In state politics, the Colorado Republican Party has embraced hardline anti-abortion stances which have included proposing laws to restrict or even ban abortion in the state.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Several hundred anti-abortion activists participate in the Rocky Mountain March for Life in Colorado each year to support ending abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Respect Life Denver also organizes an annual rally and march in the state capitol each year to support legislation against abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Since 2024, there has been increased reports of anti-abortion protestors trespassing, threatening and obstructing access to abortion clinics.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In late 2022, four out of seven council members of the city of Pueblo voted to consider a measure that would ban abortion within the city.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] The proposed ordinance was the work of a Texas-based anti-abortion group which was introduced by council member Regina Maestri.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] The proposed measure would break state laws surrounding abortion protections while observers said the measure might inspire other cities or towns throughout Colorado to attempt to ban or restrict abortions.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] The measure was narrowly rejected by the council.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] In October 2024, there was another attempt to ban abortion in Pueblo by conservative council members.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] The measure was again narrowly defeated.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] An incident of anti-abortion violence occurred at an abortion clinic in Denver, Colorado on August 26, 2003.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] On November 29, 2015, a shooting at a Planned Parenthood clinic in Colorado Springs, Colorado, left three dead and several injured, and a suspect, Robert L.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Police officer and pastor Garrett Swasey, US Iraq War veteran Ke'Arre M.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Stewart, and Hawaiian Jennifer Markovsky, who was accompanying a friend at the clinic, were killed.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] The suspect had previously acted against other clinics, and referred to himself as a "warrior for the babies" at his hearing.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] Neighbors and former neighbors described the suspect as "reclusive", and police from several states where the suspect resided described a history of run-ins dating from at least 1997.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-in-colorado] On May 11, 2016, the court declared the suspect incompetent to stand trial after a mental evaluation was completed.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] When done legally in industrialized societies, induced abortion is one of the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Modern methods use medication or surgery for abortions.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The drug mifepristone (aka RU-486) in combination with prostaglandin appears to be as safe and effective as surgery during the first and second trimesters of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Self-managed medication abortion is highly effective and safe throughout the first trimester.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The most common surgical technique involves dilating the cervix and using a suction device.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Birth control, such as contraceptive pills or intrauterine devices, can be used immediately following an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] When performed legally and safely on a woman who desires it, an induced abortion does not increase the risk of long-term mental or physical problems.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In contrast, unsafe abortions performed by unskilled individuals, with hazardous equipment, or in unsanitary facilities cause between 22,000 and 44,000 deaths and 6.9 million hospital admissions each year — responsible for between 5% and 13% of maternal deaths, especially in low-income countries.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization states that "access to legal, safe and comprehensive abortion care, including post-abortion care, is essential for the attainment of the highest possible level of sexual and reproductive health".
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Public health data show that making safe abortion legal and accessible reduces maternal deaths.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Around 73 million abortions are performed each year in the world, with about 45% done unsafely.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Abortion rates changed little between 2003 and 2008, before which they decreased for at least two decades as access to family planning and birth control increased.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] As of 2018, 37% of the world's women had access to legal abortions without limits as to reason.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Countries that permit abortions have different limits on how late in pregnancy abortion is allowed.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Abortion rates are similar between countries that restrict abortion and countries that broadly allow it, though this is partly because countries which restrict abortion tend to have higher unintended pregnancy rates.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Since 1973, there has been a global trend towards greater legal access to abortion, but there remains debate with regard to moral, religious, ethical, and legal issues.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Those who oppose abortion often argue that an embryo or fetus is a person with a right to life, and thus equate abortion with murder.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Those who support abortion's legality often argue that it is a woman's reproductive right.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Others favor legal and accessible abortion as a public health measure.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Abortion laws and views of the procedure are different around the world.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In some countries abortion is legal and women have the right to make the choice about abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In some areas, abortion is legal only in specific cases such as rape, incest, fetal defects, poverty, and risk to a woman's health.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Historically, abortions have been attempted using herbal medicines, sharp tools, forceful massage, or other traditional methods.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] An induced abortion is a medical procedure to end a pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In present-day English, the term *abortion*, when used without further qualification, generally refers to induced abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] A pregnancy can be intentionally aborted in several ways.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The abortion method depends upon the gestational age of the embryo or fetus, which gains mass as the pregnancy progresses.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Abortion laws, regional availability, and the personal preference of the woman and her doctor may inform the woman's choice of a specific abortion procedure.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Abortions can be characterized as either therapeutic or elective.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] When an abortion is performed for medical reasons, the procedure is referred to as a therapeutic abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] An abortion is referred to as elective or voluntary when it is performed at the request of the woman for non-medical reasons.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Confusion sometimes arises over the term *elective* because "elective surgery" generally refers to all scheduled surgery, whether medically necessary or not.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] About one in five pregnancies worldwide ends with an induced abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Most abortions result from unintended pregnancies.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In the United Kingdom, 1 to 2% of abortions are done because of genetic problems in the fetus.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Miscarriage, also known as spontaneous abortion, is the unintentional expulsion of an embryo or fetus before the 24th week of gestation.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] A pregnancy that ends before 37 weeks of gestation resulting in a live-born infant is a "premature birth" or a "preterm birth".
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] When a fetus dies in utero after viability, or during delivery, it is usually termed "stillborn".
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Premature births and stillbirths are generally not considered to be miscarriages, although usage of these terms can sometimes overlap.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Studies of pregnant women in the US and China have shown that between 40% and 60% of embryos do not progress to birth.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The vast majority of miscarriages occur before the woman is aware that she is pregnant, and many pregnancies spontaneously abort before medical practitioners can detect an embryo.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Between 15% and 30% of known pregnancies end in clinically apparent miscarriage, depending upon the age and health of the pregnant woman.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] 80% of these spontaneous abortions happen in the first trimester.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The most common cause of spontaneous abortion during the first trimester is chromosomal abnormalities of the embryo or fetus, accounting for at least 50% of sampled early pregnancy losses.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Other causes include vascular disease (such as lupus), diabetes, other hormonal problems, infection, and abnormalities of the uterus.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Advancing maternal age and a woman's history of previous spontaneous abortions are the two leading factors associated with a greater risk of spontaneous abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] A spontaneous abortion can also be caused by accidental trauma; intentional trauma or stress to cause miscarriage is considered induced abortion or feticide.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] may determine which abortion methods are practiced.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Medical abortions are those induced by abortifacient pharmaceuticals.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Medical abortion became an alternative method of abortion with the availability of prostaglandin analogs in the 1970s and the antiprogestogen mifepristone (also known as RU-486) in the 1980s.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimens work faster and are more effective at later gestational ages than methotrexate–misoprostol combination regimens, and combination regimens are more effective than misoprostol alone, particularly in the second trimester.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Medical abortion regimens involving mifepristone followed by misoprostol in the cheek between 24 and 48 hours later are effective when performed before 70 days' gestation.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In very early abortions, up to 7 weeks gestation, medical abortion using a mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimen is considered to be more effective than surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration), especially when clinical practice does not include detailed inspection of aspirated tissue.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Early medical abortion regimens using mifepristone, followed 24–48 hours later by buccal or vaginal misoprostol are 98% effective up to 9 weeks gestational age; from 9 to 10 weeks efficacy decreases modestly to 94%.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] If medical abortion fails, surgical abortion must be used to complete the procedure.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Early medical abortions account for the majority of abortions before 9 weeks gestation in Britain, France, Switzerland, United States, and the Nordic countries.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] A 2020 Cochrane Systematic Review concluded that providing women with medications to take home to complete the second stage of the procedure for an early medical abortion results in an effective abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Further research is required to determine if self-administered medical abortion is as safe as provider-administered medical abortion, where a health care professional is present to help manage the medical abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Safely permitting women to self-administer abortion medication has the potential to improve access to abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The review also noted a research gap concerning methods to support women who take medication at home for a self-administered abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Up to 15 weeks' gestation, suction-aspiration or vacuum aspiration are the most common surgical methods of induced abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] *Manual vacuum aspiration* (MVA) consists of removing the fetus or embryo, placenta, and membranes by suction using a manual syringe, while *electric vacuum aspiration* (EVA) uses an electric pump.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Both techniques can be used very early in pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] MVA can be used up to 14 weeks but is more often used earlier in the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] MVA, also known as "mini-suction" and "menstrual extraction", or EVA can be used in very early pregnancy when cervical dilation may not be required.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Dilation and curettage (D&C) refers to opening the cervix (dilation) and removing tissue (curettage) via suction or sharp instruments.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] D&C is a standard gynecological procedure performed for a variety of reasons, including examination of the uterine lining for possible malignancy, investigation of abnormal bleeding, and abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization recommends *sharp curettage* only when suction aspiration is unavailable.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Dilation and evacuation (D&E), used after 12 to 16 weeks, consists of opening the cervix and removing pregnancy tissue and fetal parts with suction and forceps.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] D&E is performed vaginally and does not require an incision.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Intact dilation and extraction (D&X) refers to a variant of D&E sometimes used after 18 to 20 weeks when removal of an intact fetus improves surgical safety or for other reasons.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Abortion may also be performed surgically by hysterotomy or gravid hysterectomy.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy abortion is a procedure similar to a caesarean section and is performed under general anesthesia.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] It requires a smaller incision than a caesarean section and can be used during later stages of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Gravid hysterectomy refers to removal of the whole uterus while still containing the pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy and hysterectomy are associated with much higher rates of maternal morbidity and mortality than D&E or induction abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] First trimester procedures can generally be performed using local anesthesia, while second trimester methods may require deep sedation or general anesthesia.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In places lacking the necessary medical skill for dilation and extraction, or when preferred by practitioners, an abortion can be induced by first inducing labor and then inducing fetal demise if necessary.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] This is sometimes called "induced miscarriage".
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] This procedure may be performed from 13 weeks gestation to the third trimester.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Although it is very uncommon in the United States, more than 80% of induced abortions throughout the second trimester are labor-induced abortions in Sweden and other nearby countries.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Only limited data are available comparing labor-induced abortion with the dilation and extraction method.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Unlike D&E, labor-induced abortions after 18 weeks may be complicated by the occurrence of brief fetal survival, which may be legally characterized as live birth.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] For this reason, labor-induced abortion is legally risky in the United States.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Historically, a number of herbs reputed to possess abortifacient properties have been used in folk medicine.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Such herbs include tansy, pennyroyal, black cohosh, and the now-extinct silphium.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In 1978, one woman in Colorado died and another developed organ damage when they attempted to terminate their pregnancies by taking pennyroyal oil.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Because the indiscriminant use of herbs as abortifacients can cause serious—even lethal—side effects, such as multiple organ failure, such use is not recommended by physicians.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Abortion is sometimes attempted by causing trauma to the abdomen.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The degree of force, if severe, can cause serious internal injuries without necessarily succeeding in inducing miscarriage.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In Southeast Asia, there is an ancient tradition of attempting abortion through forceful abdominal massage.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] One of the bas reliefs decorating the temple of Angkor Wat in Cambodia depicts a demon performing such an abortion upon a woman who had been sent to the underworld.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Reported methods of unsafe, self-induced abortion include misuse of misoprostol and insertion of non-surgical implements such as knitting needles and clothes hangers into the uterus.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] These and other methods to terminate pregnancy may be called "induced miscarriage".
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Such methods are rarely used in countries where surgical abortion is legal and available.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The health risks of abortion depend principally on how, and under what conditions, the procedure is performed.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) defines unsafe abortions as a procedure for terminating an unintended pregnancy carried out either by persons lacking the necessary skills or in an environment that does not conform to minimal medical standards, or both.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Legal abortions performed in the developed world are among the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] According to a 2012 study in *Obstetrics & Gynecology*, in the United States the risk of maternal mortality is 14 times lower after induced abortion than after childbirth.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The CDC estimated in 2019 that US pregnancy-related mortality was 17.2 maternal deaths per 100,000 live births, while the US abortion mortality rate was 0.43 maternal deaths per 100,000 procedures.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In the UK, guidelines of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists state that "Women should be advised that abortion is generally safer than continuing a pregnancy to term." Worldwide, on average, abortion is safer than carrying a pregnancy to term.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In the US from 2000 to 2009, abortion had a mortality rate lower than plastic surgery, lower or similar to running a marathon, and about equivalent to traveling 760 miles (1,220 km) in a passenger car.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The risk of abortion-related mortality increases with gestational age, but remains lower than that of childbirth.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Outpatient abortion is as safe from 64 to 70 days' gestation as it before 63 days.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] A 2019 study indicated that five years after seeking abortion services, women who gave birth after being denied an abortion reported worse health than women who had either first or second trimester abortions.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] There is little difference in terms of safety and efficacy between medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol and surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration) in early first trimester abortions up to 10 weeks gestation.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Medical abortion using the prostaglandin analog misoprostol alone is less effective and more painful than medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol or surgical abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Vacuum aspiration in the first trimester is the safest method of surgical abortion, and can be performed in a primary care office, abortion clinic, or hospital.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Complications, which are rare, can include uterine perforation, pelvic infection, and retained products of conception requiring a second procedure to evacuate.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Infections account for one-third of abortion-related deaths in the United States.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The rate of complications of vacuum aspiration abortion in the first trimester is similar regardless of whether the procedure is performed in a hospital, surgical center, or office.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Preventive antibiotics (such as doxycycline or metronidazole) are typically given before abortion procedures, as they are believed to substantially reduce the risk of postoperative uterine infection; however, antibiotics are not routinely given with abortion pills.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The rate of failed procedures does not appear to vary significantly depending on whether the abortion is performed by a doctor or a mid-level practitioner.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Complications after second trimester abortion are similar to those after first trimester abortion, and depend somewhat on the method chosen.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The risk of death from abortion approaches roughly half the risk of death from childbirth the farther along a woman is in pregnancy; from one in a million before 9 weeks gestation to nearly one in ten thousand at 21 weeks or more (as measured from the last menstrual period).
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] It appears that having had a prior surgical uterine evacuation (whether because of induced abortion or treatment of miscarriage) correlates with a small increase in the risk of preterm birth in future pregnancies.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The studies supporting this did not control for factors not related to abortion or miscarriage, and hence the causes of this correlation have not been determined, although multiple possibilities have been suggested.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Current evidence finds no relationship between most induced abortions and mental health problems other than those expected for any unwanted pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Some older reviews concluded that abortion was associated with an increased risk of psychological problems; however, later reviews of the medical literature found that previous reviews did not use an appropriate control group.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] When a control group is utilized, receiving abortion is not associated with adverse psychological outcomes.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] However, women seeking abortion who are denied access to abortion have an increase in anxiety after the denial.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Although some studies show negative mental-health outcomes in women who choose abortions after the first trimester because of fetal abnormalities, more rigorous research would be needed to show this conclusively.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Some proposed negative psychological effects of abortion have been referred to by anti-abortion advocates as a separate condition called "post-abortion syndrome", but this is not recognized by medical or psychological professionals in the United States.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] A 2020 long term-study among US women found that about 99% of women felt that they made the right decision five years after they had an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Relief was the primary emotion with few women feeling sadness or guilt.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Social stigma was a main factor predicting negative emotions and regret years later.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Some purported risks of abortion are promoted primarily by anti-abortion groups, but lack scientific support.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] For example, the question of a link between induced abortion and breast cancer has been investigated extensively.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Major medical and scientific bodies (including the WHO, National Cancer Institute, American Cancer Society, Royal College of OBGYN and American Congress of OBGYN) have concluded that abortion does not cause breast cancer.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In the past even illegality has not automatically meant that the abortions were unsafe.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] A 1940s American physician spoke of his pride in having performed 13,844 illegal abortions without any fatalities.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In 1870s New York City, the abortionist/midwife Madame Restell (Anna Trow Lohman) is said to have lost very few women among her more than 100,000 patients—a lower mortality rate than the childbirth mortality rate at the time.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In 1936, obstetrics and gynecology professor Frederick J.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Women seeking an abortion may use unsafe methods, especially when abortion is legally restricted.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] They may attempt self-induced abortion or seek the help of a person without proper medical training or facilities.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] This can lead to severe complications, such as incomplete abortion, sepsis, hemorrhage, and damage to internal organs.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are a major cause of injury and death among women worldwide.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Although data are imprecise, it is estimated that approximately 20 million unsafe abortions are performed annually, with 97% taking place in developing countries.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are believed to result in millions of injuries.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Estimates of deaths vary according to methodology, and have ranged from 37,000 to 70,000 in the past decade; deaths from unsafe abortion account for around 13% of all maternal deaths.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization believes that mortality has fallen since the 1990s.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] To reduce the number of unsafe abortions, public health organizations have generally advocated emphasizing the legalization of abortion, training of medical personnel, and ensuring access to reproductive-health services.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] A major factor in whether abortions are performed safely or not is the legal standing of abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Countries with restrictive abortion laws have higher rates of unsafe abortion and similar overall abortion rates compared to countries where abortion is legal and available.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] For example, the 1996 legalization of abortion in South Africa led to an immediate reduction in abortion-related complications, with abortion-related deaths dropping by more than 90%.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Similar reductions in maternal mortality have been observed after other countries have liberalized their abortion laws, such as Romania and Nepal.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] A 2011 study concluded that in the United States, some state-level anti-abortion laws are correlated with lower rates of abortion in that state.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The analysis, however, did not take into account travel to other states without such laws to obtain an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In addition, a lack of access to effective contraception contributes to unsafe abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] It has been estimated that the incidence of unsafe abortion could be reduced by up to 75% (from 20 million to 5 million annually) if modern family planning and maternal health services were readily available globally.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Rates of such abortions may be difficult to measure because they can be reported variously as miscarriage, "induced miscarriage", "menstrual regulation", "mini-abortion", and "regulation of a delayed/suspended menstruation".
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Forty percent of the world's women are able to access therapeutic and elective abortions within gestational limits, while an additional 35 percent have access to legal abortion if they meet certain physical, mental, or socioeconomic criteria.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] While maternal mortality seldom results from safe abortions, unsafe abortions result in 70,000 deaths and 5 million disabilities per year.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Complications of unsafe abortion account for approximately an eighth of maternal mortalities worldwide, though this varies by region.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Secondary infertility caused by an unsafe abortion affects an estimated 24 million women.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The rate of unsafe abortions has increased from 44% to 49% between 1995 and 2008.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Health education, access to family planning, and improvements in health care during and after abortion have been proposed to address consequences of unsafe abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In many places, where abortion is illegal or carries a heavy social stigma, medical reporting of abortion is not reliable.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] For this reason, estimates of the incidence of abortion must be made without determining certainty related to standard error.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The number of abortions performed worldwide was characterized as stable in the early 2000s, with 41.6 million having been performed in 2003 and 43.8 million having been performed in 2008.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The abortion rate worldwide was 28 per 1000 women per year, though it was 24 per 1000 women per year for developed countries and 29 per 1000 women per year for developing countries.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The same 2012 study indicated that in 2008, the estimated abortion percentage of known pregnancies was at 21% worldwide, with 26% in developed countries and 20% in developing countries.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] On average, the incidence of abortion is similar in countries with restrictive abortion laws and those with more liberal access to abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Restrictive abortion laws are associated with increases in the percentage of abortions performed unsafely.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The rate of legal, induced abortion varies extensively worldwide.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] According to the report of employees of Guttmacher Institute it ranged from 7 per 1000 women per year (Germany and Switzerland) to 30 per 1000 women per year (Estonia) in countries with complete statistics in 2008.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The proportion of pregnancies that ended in induced abortion ranged from about 10% (Israel, the Netherlands and Switzerland) to 30% (Estonia) in the same group, though it might be as high as 36% in Hungary and Romania, whose statistics were deemed incomplete.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] An American study in 2002 concluded that about half of women having abortions were using a form of contraception at the time of becoming pregnant.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Inconsistent use was reported by half of those using condoms and three-quarters of those using the birth control pill; 42% of those using condoms reported failure through slipping or breakage.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Of the other half of women, who were not using contraception at the time of becoming pregnant, the vast majority had used contraception at some point in the past, indicating some level of dissatisfaction with the contraceptive options available to them.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Indeed, 32% of these contraceptive nonusers cited concerns about contraceptive methods as their reason for nonuse, and a more recent study found similar results.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Taken together, these statistics suggest that new contraceptive methods, such as non-hormonal contraceptives or male contraceptives, could reduce unintended pregnancy and abortion rates.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute has found that "most abortions in the United States are obtained by minority women" because minority women "have much higher rates of unintended pregnancy".
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] in England and Wales during 2019 (left).
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Abortion in the United States by gestational age, 2016 (right).
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Abortion rates vary depending on the stage of pregnancy and the method practiced.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] 91% of these were classified as having been done by "curettage" (suction-aspiration, dilation and curettage, dilation and evacuation), 8% by "medical" means (mifepristone), >1% by "intrauterine instillation" (saline or prostaglandin), and 1% by "other" (including hysterotomy and hysterectomy).
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] According to the CDC, due to data collection difficulties the data must be viewed as tentative and some fetal deaths reported beyond 20 weeks may be natural deaths erroneously classified as abortions if the removal of the dead fetus is accomplished by the same procedure as an induced abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute estimated there were 2,200 intact dilation and extraction procedures in the US during 2000; this accounts for <0.2% of the total number of abortions performed that year.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Similarly, in England and Wales in 2006, 89% of terminations occurred at or under 12 weeks, 9% between 13 and 19 weeks, and 2% at or over 20 weeks.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] 64% of those reported were by vacuum aspiration, 6% by D&E, and 30% were medical.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] There are more second trimester abortions in developing countries such as China, India and Vietnam than in developed countries.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] There are both medical and non-medical reasons to have an abortion later in pregnancy (after 20 weeks).
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] A study was conducted from 2008 to 2010 at the University of California San Francisco where more than 440 women were asked about why they experienced delays in obtaining abortion care, if there were any.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] This study found that almost half of individuals who obtained an abortion after 20 weeks did not suspect that they were pregnant until later in their pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Other barriers to abortion care found in the study included lack of information about where to access an abortion, difficulties with transportation, lack of insurance coverage, and inability to pay for the abortion procedure.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Medical reasons for seeking an abortion later in pregnancy include fetal anomalies and health risk to the pregnant person.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] There are prenatal tests that can diagnose Down Syndrome or cystic fibrosis as early as 10 weeks into gestation, but structural fetal anomalies are often detected much later in pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] A proportion of structural fetal anomalies are lethal, which means that the fetus will almost certainly die before or shortly after birth.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Life-threatening conditions may also develop later in pregnancy, such as early severe preeclampsia, newly diagnosed cancer in need of urgent treatment, and intrauterine infection (chorioamnionitis), which often occurs along with premature rupture of the amniotic sac (PPROM).
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] If serious medical conditions such as these arise before the fetus is viable, the person carrying the pregnancy may pursue an abortion to preserve their own health.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The reasons why women have abortions are diverse and vary across the world.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Some of the reasons may include an inability to afford a child, domestic violence, lack of support, feeling they are too young, and the wish to complete education or advance a career.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Additional reasons include not being able or willing to raise a child conceived as a result of rape or incest.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Some abortions are undergone as the result of societal pressures.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] These factors can sometimes result in compulsory abortion or sex-selective abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In cultures where there is a preference for male children, some women have sex selective abortions, which have partially replaced the earlier practice of female infanticide.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Some abortions are performed due to concerns over maternal health.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In 1990s, women cited maternal health as their main motivating factor in about a third of abortions in three of 27 countries analyzed.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In seven additional countries, about 7% of abortions were maternal health related.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In the U.S., the Supreme Court decisions in *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Bolton*: "ruled that the state's interest in the life of the fetus became compelling only at the point of viability, defined as the point at which the fetus can survive independently of its mother.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Even after the point of viability, the state cannot favor the life of the fetus over the life or health of the pregnant woman.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Under the right of privacy, physicians must be free to use their "medical judgment for the preservation of the life or health of the mother".
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] On the same day that the Court decided Roe, it also decided Doe v.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Bolton, in which the Court defined health very broadly: "The medical judgment may be exercised in the light of all factors—physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the woman's age—relevant to the well-being of the patient.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The rate of cancer during pregnancy is 0.02–1%, and in many cases, cancer of the mother leads to consideration of abortion to protect the life of the mother, or in response to the potential damage that may occur to the fetus during treatment.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] This is particularly true for cervical cancer, the most common type of which occurs in 1 of every 2,000–13,000 pregnancies, for which initiation of treatment "cannot co-exist with preservation of fetal life (unless neoadjuvant chemotherapy is chosen)".
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Very early stage cervical cancers (I and IIa) may be treated by radical hysterectomy and pelvic lymph node dissection, radiation therapy, or both, while later stages are treated by radiotherapy.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Chemotherapy may be used simultaneously.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Treatment of breast cancer during pregnancy also involves fetal considerations, because lumpectomy is discouraged in favor of modified radical mastectomy unless late-term pregnancy allows follow-up radiation therapy to be administered after the birth.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Exposure to a single chemotherapy drug is estimated to cause a 7.5–17% risk of teratogenic effects on the fetus, with higher risks for multiple drug treatments.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Treatment with more than 40 Gy of radiation usually causes spontaneous abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Exposure to much lower doses during the first trimester, especially 8 to 15 weeks of development, can cause intellectual disability or microcephaly, and exposure at this or subsequent stages can cause reduced intrauterine growth and birth weight.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Exposures above 0.005–0.025 Gy cause a dose-dependent reduction in IQ.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] It is possible to greatly reduce exposure to radiation with abdominal shielding, depending on how far the area to be irradiated is from the fetus.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The process of birth itself may also put the mother at risk.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Congenital disorders, revealed by prenatal screening, motivate some women to seek abortions.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Health outcomes of preterm births include a significant probability of long-term neurodevelopmental impairment before gestational age of 29 weeks, with a higher probability with decreasing gestational age.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In the United States, public opinion shifted after television personality Sherri Finkbine's was exposed to thalidomide, a teratogen, in her fifth month of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Unable to obtain a legal abortion in the United States, Finkbine traveled to Sweden.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] From 1962 to 1965, an outbreak of German measles left 15,000 babies with severe birth defects.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In 1967, the American Medical Association publicly supported liberalization of abortion laws.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] A National Opinion Research Center poll in 1965 showed 73% supported abortion when the mother's life was at risk, 57% when birth defects were present and 59% for pregnancies resulting from rape or incest.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Since ancient times, abortions have been done using a number of methods, including herbal medicines acting as abortifacients, sharp tools through the use of force, or through other traditional medicine methods.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Induced abortion has a long history and can be traced back to civilizations as varied as ancient China (abortifacient knowledge is often attributed to the mythological ruler Shennong), ancient India since its Vedic age, ancient Egypt with its Ebers Papyrus (c.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] 1550 BCE), and the Roman Empire in the time of Juvenal (c.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] One of the earliest known artistic representations of abortion is in a bas relief at Angkor Wat (c.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Found in a series of friezes that represent judgment after death in Hindu and Buddhist culture, it depicts the technique of abdominal abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In *Politics* (350 BCE), Aristotle condemned infanticide as a means of population control.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] He preferred abortion in such cases, with the restriction that it "must be practised on it before it has developed sensation and life; for the line between lawful and unlawful abortion will be marked by the fact of having sensation and being alive".
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Abortion has been a fairly common practice, and was not always illegal or controversial until the 19th century.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In Europe and North America, abortion techniques advanced starting in the 17th century; the conservatism of most in the medical profession with regards to sexual matters prevented the wide expansion of abortion techniques.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Other medical practitioners in addition to some physicians advertised their services, and they were not widely regulated until the 19th century when the practice, sometimes called *restellism*, was banned in both the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Some 19th-century physicians, argued for anti-abortion laws on racist and misogynist as well as moral grounds.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Church groups were also highly influential in anti-abortion movements, and religious groups more so since the 20th century.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Some of the early anti-abortion laws punished only the doctor or abortionist, and while women could be criminally tried for a self-induced abortion, they were rarely prosecuted in general.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Some maintain that in the 19th century early abortions under the hygienic conditions in which midwives usually worked were relatively safe.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Several scholars argue that, despite improved medical procedures, the period from the 1930s until the 1970s saw more zealous enforcement of anti-abortion laws, alongside an increasing control of abortion providers by organized crime.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In 1920, Soviet Russia became the first country to legalize abortion after Lenin insisted that no woman be forced to give birth.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Abortion was then legalized in some form in Iceland (1935), Sweden (1938), Nazi Germany (1935) and Japan (1948) Beginning in the second half of the 20th century, abortion was legalized in a greater number of countries.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In the Catholic Church, opinion was divided on how serious abortion was in comparison with such acts as contraception and oral or anal sex.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The Catholic Church did not begin vigorously opposing abortion until the 19th century.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] As early as ~100 CE, the *Didache* taught that abortion was sinful.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Several historians argue that prior to the 19th century most Catholic authors did not regard termination of pregnancy before quickening or ensoulment as an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] 1585–1590) was the first Pope to institute a Church policy labeling all abortion as homicide and condemning abortion regardless of the stage of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Sixtus V's pronouncement was reversed in 1591 by Pope Gregory XIV.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In the recodification of 1917 Code of Canon Law, *Apostolicae Sedis* was strengthened, in part to remove a possible reading that excluded excommunication of the mother.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Statements made in the *Catechism of the Catholic Church*, the codified summary of the Church's teachings, considers abortion from the moment of conception as homicide and called for the end of legal abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Denominations that support abortion rights with some limits include the United Methodist Church, Episcopal Church, Evangelical Lutheran Church in America and Presbyterian Church USA.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] A 2014 Guttmacher survey of abortion patients in the United States found that many reported a religious affiliation: 24% were Catholic while 30% were Protestant.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] A 1995 survey reported that Catholic women are as likely as the general population to terminate a pregnancy, Protestants are less likely to do so, and evangelical Christians are the least likely to do so.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] A 2019 Pew Research Center study found that most Christian denominations were against overturning *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Wade,* which in the United States legalized abortion, at around 70%, except White Evangelicals at 35%.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In Judaism, the fetus is not considered to have a human soul until it is safely outside of the woman, is viable, and has taken its first breath.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] The fetus is considered valuable property of the woman and not a human life while in the womb (Exodus 21:22-23).
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] While Judaism encourages people to be fruitful and multiply by having children, abortion is allowed and is deemed necessary when a pregnant woman's life is in danger.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Several religions, including Judaism, which disagree that human life begins at conception, support the legality of abortion on religious freedom grounds.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] In Islam, abortion is traditionally permitted until a point in time when Muslims believe the soul enters the fetus, considered by various theologians to be at conception, 40 days after conception, 120 days after conception, or at quickening.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Abortion is largely heavily restricted or forbidden in areas of high Islamic faith such as the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Hindu views on abortion are diverse and lack a single authoritative position, shaped by principles like ahimsa (non-violence), karma, and reincarnation, which typically regard it as morally wrong for interrupting the soul's cycle.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Scriptures often equate abortion to grave sins, with the fetus considered ensouled from conception or early gestation.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] However, it may be ethically permissible to save the mother's life or in cases of severe fetal abnormalities, prioritizing lesser harm.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p01] Modern opinions differ regionally: In India, a majority view abortion as generally illegal, while in the US, most Hindus support legal access in all or most cases.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Induced abortion has long been the source of considerable debate.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Ethical, moral, philosophical, biological, religious and legal issues surrounding abortion are related to value systems.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Opinions of abortion may be about fetal rights, governmental authority, and women's rights.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] In both public and private debate, arguments presented in favor of or against abortion access focus on either the moral permissibility of an induced abortion, or the justification of laws permitting or restricting abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] The World Medical Association Declaration on Therapeutic Abortion notes, "circumstances bringing the interests of a mother into conflict with the interests of her unborn child create a dilemma and raise the question as to whether or not the pregnancy should be deliberately terminated".
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Abortion debates, especially pertaining to abortion laws, are often spearheaded by groups advocating one of these two positions.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Groups who favor greater legal restrictions on abortion, including complete prohibition, most often describe themselves as "pro-life" while groups who are against such legal restrictions describe themselves as "pro-choice".
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] The median voters stance on abortion varies by jurisdiction and can result in swing votes.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Current laws pertaining to abortion are diverse.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Religious, moral, and cultural factors continue to influence abortion laws throughout the world.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] The right to life, the right to liberty, the right to security of person, and the right to reproductive health are major issues of human rights that sometimes constitute the basis for the existence or absence of abortion laws.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] In jurisdictions where abortion is legal, certain requirements must often be met before a woman may obtain a legal abortion (an abortion performed without the woman's consent is considered feticide and is generally illegal).
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] These requirements usually depend on the age of the fetus, often using a trimester-based system to regulate the window of legality, or as in the U.S., on a doctor's evaluation of the fetus' viability.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Some jurisdictions require a waiting period before the procedure, prescribe the distribution of information on fetal development, or require that parents be contacted if their minor daughter requests an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Many restrictions are waived in emergency situations.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] China, which has ended their one-child policy, and now has a three-child policy, has at times incorporated mandatory abortions as part of their population control strategy.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Other jurisdictions ban abortion almost entirely.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Many, but not all, of these allow legal abortions in a variety of circumstances.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] These circumstances vary based on jurisdiction, but may include whether the pregnancy is a result of rape or incest, the fetus' development is impaired, the woman's physical or mental well-being is endangered, or socioeconomic considerations make childbirth a hardship.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] In countries where abortion is banned entirely, such as Nicaragua, medical authorities have recorded rises in maternal death directly and indirectly due to pregnancy as well as deaths due to doctors' fears of prosecution if they treat other gynecological emergencies.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Some countries, such as Bangladesh, that nominally ban abortion, may also support clinics that perform abortions under the guise of menstrual hygiene.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] This is also a terminology in traditional medicine.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] In places where abortion is illegal or carries heavy social stigma, pregnant women may engage in medical tourism and travel to countries where they can terminate their pregnancies.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Women on Waves has provided medication abortion and education on a ship in international waters off the coast of countries with restrictive abortion laws.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Women without the means to travel can resort to providers of illegal abortions or attempt to perform an abortion by themselves.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Sonography and amniocentesis allow parents to determine sex before childbirth.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] The development of this technology has led to sex-selective abortion, or the termination of a fetus based on its sex.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] The selective termination of a female fetus is most common.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Sex-selective abortion is partially responsible for the noticeable disparities between the birth rates of male and female children in some countries.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] The preference for male children is reported in many areas of Asia, and abortion used to limit female births has been reported in Taiwan, South Korea, India, and China.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] This deviation from the standard birth rates of males and females occurs despite the fact that the country in question may have officially banned sex-selective abortion or even sex-screening.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Many countries have taken legislative steps to reduce the incidence of sex-selective abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] At the International Conference on Population and Development in 1994 over 180 states agreed to eliminate "all forms of discrimination against the girl child and the root causes of son preference", conditions also condemned by a PACE resolution in 2011.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] On the other hand, measures to reduce gender inequality can reduce the prevalence of such abortions without attendant negative consequences.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Abortion providers and facilities have been subjected to violence, including murder, assault, arson, and bombing.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Some scholars consider anti-abortion violence to be within the definition of terrorism, a view shared by some governments.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] In the U.S. and Canada, over 8,000 incidents of violence, trespassing, and death threats have been recorded by providers since 1977, including over 200 bombings/arsons and hundreds of assaults.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Abortion clinics have also been targeted by acid attacks, invasions, and vandalism The majority of abortion opponents have not been involved in violent acts.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Physicians and other abortion clinic staff have been murdered by abortion opponents.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] In the United States, at least four physicians have been murdered in connection with their work at abortion clinics, including David Gunn (1993), John Britton (1994), Barnett Slepian (1998), and George Tiller (2009).
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] In Canada, gynecologist Garson Romalis survived murder attempts in both 1994 and 2000.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Besides physicians, killings have targeted other clinic staff, such as John Salvi's 1994 murder of two receptionists in Massachusetts clinic and Peter Knight's 2001 murder of a security guard in a Melbourne clinic.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Notable perpetrators of anti-abortion violence include Eric Rudolph, Scott Roeder, Shelley Shannon, and Paul Hill, the first person to be executed in the United States for murdering an abortion provider.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Some countries have laws to protecting access to abortion.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Such laws prevent abortion opponents from interfering with access to legal abortion services.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] For example, the American Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act bars the use of threats or violence to interfere with abortion access.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Abortion access laws may also establish safe access zones around abortion clinics, with limits on protests and enhanced penalties for anti-abortion violence.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Psychological pressure may also be used to limit abortion access.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Some protestors record women entering clinics on camera.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Spontaneous abortion occurs in various animals.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] For example, in sheep it may be caused by stress or physical exertion, such as crowding through doors or being chased by dogs.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] In cows, abortion may be caused by contagious disease, such as brucellosis or *Campylobacter*, but can often be controlled by vaccination.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Eating pine needles can also induce abortions in cows.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Several plants, including broomweed, skunk cabbage, poison hemlock, and tree tobacco, are known to cause fetal deformities and abortion in cattle, and in sheep and goats.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] In horses, a fetus may be aborted or resorbed if it has lethal white syndrome.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Foal embryos that are homozygous for the dominant white gene (WW) are theorized to also be aborted or resorbed before birth.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] In many species of sharks and rays, stress-induced abortions occur frequently upon capture.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Viral infection can cause abortion in dogs.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Cats can experience spontaneous abortion for many reasons, including hormonal imbalance.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] A combined abortion and spaying are performed on pregnant cats, especially in trap–neuter–return programs, to prevent unwanted kittens from being born.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Female rodents may terminate a pregnancy when exposed to the smell of a male not responsible for the pregnancy, known as the Bruce effect.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Abortion may also be induced in animals, in the context of animal husbandry.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] For example, abortion may be induced in mares that have been mated improperly, or that have been purchased by owners who did not realize the mares were pregnant, or that are pregnant with twin foals.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Feticide can occur in horses and zebras due to male harassment of pregnant mares or forced copulation, although the frequency in the wild has been questioned.
[src:abortion-in-colorado/abortion-p02] Male gray langur monkeys may attack females following male takeover, causing miscarriage.
